The person referred to in v. 184 is the ‘ structor' mentioned S. v. 120, where see note. ‘ Pulmentaria' are savoury dishes, or sauces (see note on Horace, Epp. i. 18. 48), and the reading which Lachmann has invented and Jahn adopted, ‘condiat‚' 15 quite out of place. ‘Condat’ is here to make up. The reading of most MSS. is ‘condit,' and some have ‘componit' to correspond. But the subjunctive is wanted [Ribbeck has ‘ condit’]. There will be a man to arrange the courses and make up the savoury messes.
